}
```

**Atlas:**

Atlas Cluster

```json
{
  "$out": {
    "atlas": {
      "projectId": "<atlas-project-ID>",
      "clusterName": "<atlas-cluster-name>",
      "db": "<atlas-database-name>",
      "coll": "<atlas-collection-name>"
    }
  }
}
```

> **Example:** You want to write 90 MiB of data to JSON (Javascript Object Notation) files to an S3 (Simple Storage Service)
> bucket named `my-s3-bucket`.
>
> Using the following $out syntax:
>
> ```json
> {
>   "$out": {
>     "s3": {
>       "bucket": "my-s3-bucket",
>       "region": "us-east-1",
>       "filename": {"$toString": "$saleDate"},
>       "format": {
>         "name": "json",
>         "maxFileSize": "100MiB"
>       }
>     }
>   }
> }
> ```
>
> $out writes 90 MiB of data to JSON (Javascript Object Notation) files in the root of the
> bucket. Each JSON (Javascript Object Notation) file contains all of the documents with the
> same `saleDate` value. $out names each file using the
> documents' `saleDate` value converted to a string.

> **Example:** You want to write 90 MiB of data to JSON (Javascript Object Notation) files to an Azure (Microsoft Azure) Blob Storage
> container named `my-container`.
>
> Using the following $out syntax:
>
> ```json
> {
>   "$out": {
>     "azure": {
>       "serviceURL": "http://mystorageaccount.blob.core.windows.net/",
>       "container": "my-container",
>       "region": "eastus2",
>       "filename": {"$toString": "$saleDate"},
>       "format": {
>         "name": "json",
>         "maxFileSize": "100MiB"
>       }
>     }
>   }
> }
> ```
>
> $out writes 90 MiB of data to JSON (Javascript Object Notation) files in the root of the
> container. Each JSON (Javascript Object Notation) file contains all of the documents with the
> same `saleDate` value. $out names each file using the
> documents' `saleDate` value converted to a string.

> **Example:** You want to write 90 MiB of data to JSON (Javascript Object Notation) files to a Google Cloud Storage
> bucket named `my-gcs-bucket`.
>
> Using the following $out syntax:
>
> ```json
> {
>   "$out": {
>     "gcs": {
>       "bucket": "my-gcs-bucket",
>       "region": "us-central1",
>       "filename": {"$toString": "$saleDate"},
>       "format": {
>         "name": "json",
>         "maxFileSize": "100MiB"
>       }
>     }
>   }
> }
> ```
>
> $out writes 90 MiB of data to JSON (Javascript Object Notation) files in the root of the
> bucket. Each JSON (Javascript Object Notation) file contains all of the documents with the
> same `saleDate` value. $out names each file using the
> documents' `saleDate` value converted to a string.

This $out syntax sends the aggregated data to a
`sampleDB.mySampleData` collection in the Atlas cluster
named `myTestCluster`. The syntax doesn't specify a project ID;
$out uses the ID of the project that contains your federated database instance.

> **Example:**&#x20;
>
> ```json
> {
>   "$out": {
>     "atlas": {
>       "clusterName": "myTestCluster",
>       "db": "sampleDB",
>       "coll": "mySampleData"
>     }
>   }
> }
> ```

The following example shows $out syntax for running an aggregation
pipeline that ends with the $out stage in the background.

**S3:**

S3

> **Example:**&#x20;
>
> ```json
> db.runCommand({
>   "aggregate": "my-collection",
>   "pipeline": [
>     {
>       "$out": {
>         "s3": {
>           "bucket": "my-s3-bucket",
>           "filename": { "$toString": "$saleDate" }
>           "format": {
>             "name": "json"
>           }
>         }
>       }
>     }
>   ],
>   { "background" : true }
> })
> ```
>
> $out writes to JSON (Javascript Object Notation) files in the root of the bucket in the
> background. Each JSON (Javascript Object Notation) file contains all of the documents
> with the same `saleDate` value. $out names each file using
> the documents' `saleDate` value converted to a string.

